WEBVTT

00:01.802 --> 00:06.371
A luxury voyage
becomes a living nightmare.

00:06.373 --> 00:08.140
HEAD:
Water starts to come in.

00:08.142 --> 00:12.911
People are screaming.
It's a terrifying situation.

00:12.913 --> 00:16.681
A Soviet agent
hiding in plain sight.

00:16.683 --> 00:18.683
ELEVADO:
He offered himself to the KGB

00:18.685 --> 00:21.820
because of the adventure
and the intrigue.

00:23.824 --> 00:27.759
And a terrible journey through
the Alaskan Tundra.

00:27.761 --> 00:30.462
HURLEY:
It was cold. It was remote.

00:30.464 --> 00:32.664
This was a sure death sentence.

00:32.666 --> 00:34.766
♪♪

00:34.768 --> 00:37.636
These are the mysteries
at the museum.

00:37.638 --> 00:44.276
♪♪

00:44.278 --> 00:48.146
Southeast Utah is home to one of
the most spectacular landscapes

00:48.148 --> 00:52.818
in the country,
Arches National Park.

00:52.820 --> 00:54.886
This majestic expanse is home

00:54.888 --> 00:58.824
to more than 2,000
striking sandstone arches

00:58.826 --> 01:03.028
that stretch up to 300 feet
in width.

01:03.030 --> 01:05.763
And on the edge of the park,
in the town of Moab,

01:05.765 --> 01:09.734
is an institution that
celebrates the region's history,

01:09.736 --> 01:12.670
Museum of Moab.

01:12.672 --> 01:14.005
The collection includes

01:14.007 --> 01:17.742
a sheriff's revolver from 1898,

01:17.744 --> 01:21.713
a 19th century gas lamp
used by miners,

01:21.715 --> 01:24.649
and a special ax
developed in 1910

01:24.651 --> 01:28.220
to help the U.S. Forest Service
fight wildfires.

01:31.658 --> 01:34.559
But among these perfectly
preserved antiques

01:34.561 --> 01:37.329
is a rugged modern object.

01:37.331 --> 01:40.398
It's about 6 feet long
and about 2 feet wide.

01:40.400 --> 01:44.068
It's black, orange,
and silver in color.

01:44.070 --> 01:48.907
There are dark nylon straps
and locking clips.

01:48.909 --> 01:52.377
WILDMAN: This artifact recalls
a chilling brush with death

01:52.379 --> 01:54.513
and a 4-legged hero
who saved the day.

01:54.515 --> 01:57.282
[ Dog barks ]
MARSHALL: This is the story
of a woman, her dog,

01:57.284 --> 01:59.952
and a terrifying fight
for survival.

01:59.954 --> 02:05.157
♪♪

02:05.159 --> 02:08.360
WILDMAN: December 2006. Utah.

02:08.362 --> 02:11.429
35 year-old Danelle Ballengee
is out for a run

02:11.431 --> 02:15.067
in this remote canyon
outside Moab.

02:15.069 --> 02:18.837
Alongside her is
her beloved dog, Taz.

02:18.839 --> 02:22.441
She took that dog everywhere.
That dog was a part of her.

02:22.443 --> 02:24.176
WILDMAN: Ballengee
is a world-class athlete

02:24.178 --> 02:25.444
and mountain climber

02:25.446 --> 02:28.079
with experience
tackling tough terrain,

02:28.081 --> 02:31.116
but today, she's following
a simple trail.

02:31.118 --> 02:34.753
She had run this trail before.
It wasn't her first time there.

02:36.257 --> 02:38.590
WILDMAN:
Then 4 miles into the run,

02:38.592 --> 02:43.395
her routine workout becomes
a nightmare.

02:43.397 --> 02:46.765
Ballengee slips and takes
a terrifying tumble

02:46.767 --> 02:48.967
over the edge of a canyon.

02:48.969 --> 02:52.670
She was already heading down
a very, very steep angle.

02:52.672 --> 02:54.506
There was no arresting
this fall.

02:54.508 --> 02:59.611
♪♪

02:59.613 --> 03:01.813
WILDMAN: Finally,
Ballengee comes to a halt

03:01.815 --> 03:04.149
at the bottom of the canyon.

03:04.151 --> 03:07.218
When she tries to move,
she feels a searing pain

03:07.220 --> 03:09.354
shoot through her pelvis.

03:09.356 --> 03:12.290
She suspects it's broken.

03:12.292 --> 03:15.093
Then she has
a horrifying realization.

03:15.095 --> 03:17.562
She left for her run
without telling anyone

03:17.564 --> 03:18.830
where she was going.

03:20.901 --> 03:23.435
Even if her friends
figure out she's missing,

03:23.437 --> 03:25.704
they'll have no idea
where to find her.

03:29.143 --> 03:31.510
Ballengee has no phone.

03:31.512 --> 03:33.778
All she has is a water bottle,

03:33.780 --> 03:35.981
a small packet of energy gel,

03:35.983 --> 03:40.719
and her trusty dog Taz,
who was uninjured in the fall.

03:40.721 --> 03:42.787
-Help!
-Ballengee screams for help

03:42.789 --> 03:46.724
in hopes that someone
might hear her cries.

03:46.726 --> 03:50.528
But hours pass
and no one comes.

03:50.530 --> 03:51.830
MARSHALL: It's way beyond
feeling desperate.

03:51.832 --> 03:54.800
She was truly
in a dire situation.

03:54.802 --> 03:57.169
Help!

03:57.171 --> 03:58.603
♪♪

03:58.605 --> 04:00.472
WILDMAN: By the evening
of her second day,

04:00.474 --> 04:02.874
Ballengee is
on the verge of death.

04:02.876 --> 04:04.676
♪♪

04:04.678 --> 04:06.811
But all is not lost.

04:06.813 --> 04:09.815
Ballengee still has
one last hope --

04:09.817 --> 04:11.750
her dog Taz.

04:11.752 --> 04:13.085
[ Taz barks ]

04:13.087 --> 04:16.288
MARSHALL: Out of desperation,
she said to her dog Taz,

04:16.290 --> 04:20.625
"You need to find help. You need
to bring someone back here."

04:20.627 --> 04:23.362
WILDMAN: Seeming to understand
her instructions,

04:23.364 --> 04:27.632
Taz bounds up and out
of the canyon.

04:27.634 --> 04:29.568
The dog took off.

04:29.570 --> 04:31.035
She didn't know
where he was going.

04:31.037 --> 04:33.705
She didn't know
if he really understood.

04:33.707 --> 04:36.642
[ Taz barks ]

04:36.644 --> 04:39.544
WILDMAN: Ballengee waits alone
at the bottom of the canyon,

04:39.546 --> 04:42.547
wondering if she will ever
live to see her dog again.

04:42.549 --> 04:46.618
♪♪

04:46.620 --> 04:50.588
And just when all seems lost,
something incredible happens.

04:50.590 --> 04:52.324
[ Taz barks ]

04:52.326 --> 04:55.727
Taz returns.

04:55.729 --> 04:57.362
MARSHALL:
When she saw the dog come back,

04:57.364 --> 05:00.265
the tears were coming
down her cheeks.

05:00.267 --> 05:03.168
WILDMAN: And the clever canine
is not alone.

05:03.170 --> 05:05.871
Taz has brought a search party.

05:05.873 --> 05:07.205
Among them is

05:07.207 --> 05:09.608
Grand County Search and Rescue
Officer John Marshall.

05:09.610 --> 05:13.145
MARSHALL: I've been doing search
and rescue here for 15 years,

05:13.147 --> 05:16.013
and I've never seen anything
like this.

05:16.015 --> 05:20.552
That dog was truly the hero
in this story.

05:20.554 --> 05:22.153
WILDMAN: The team
carefully loads Ballengee

05:22.155 --> 05:23.989
onto a stretcher,

05:23.991 --> 05:28.760
the same one on display
at Museum of Moab in Utah,

05:28.762 --> 05:31.062
and rushes her to the hospital.

05:31.064 --> 05:32.497
[ Taz barks ]

05:32.499 --> 05:34.566
Ballengee learns that
her friends had noticed

05:34.568 --> 05:35.834
she was missing

05:35.836 --> 05:37.502
and had organized
a search party

05:37.504 --> 05:39.838
to comb the very canyon
where she'd been running.

05:39.840 --> 05:41.907
-[ Taz barks ]
-They were at the trailhead

05:41.909 --> 05:45.710
when Taz ran out of the canyon
to meet them.

05:45.712 --> 05:49.448
The loyal canine then led them
back to where she had fallen.

05:49.450 --> 05:51.049
It was truly astonishing.

05:51.051 --> 05:53.184
This dog was on a mission.

05:53.186 --> 05:55.987
He was saying, "I know what
you're looking for.

05:55.989 --> 05:57.789
Hey, follow me."

05:57.791 --> 06:02.193
♪♪

06:02.195 --> 06:04.529
WILDMAN: Danelle Ballengee
makes a full recovery

06:04.531 --> 06:06.531
and continues
to pursue her passion

06:06.533 --> 06:08.967
as an adventure athlete.

06:08.969 --> 06:11.736
But now, before she heads out,
she always tells people

06:11.738 --> 06:15.106
where she and her beloved dog
are going.

06:15.108 --> 06:18.810
MARSHALL: Today, Taz
and Ballengee still train.

06:18.812 --> 06:21.913
They still compete
and they still run together.

06:21.915 --> 06:27.418
♪♪

06:27.420 --> 06:29.621
WILDMAN: The stretcher used
to rescue Ballengee

06:29.623 --> 06:33.458
is on display
at Museum of Moab in Utah.

06:33.460 --> 06:35.627
It recalls a life-saving moment

06:35.629 --> 06:40.098
and the canine companion who
truly was a woman's best friend.

06:40.100 --> 06:43.301
♪♪

06:43.303 --> 06:44.902
Allentown, Pennsylvania.

06:44.904 --> 06:49.674
In 1777, Continental soldiers
smuggled the Liberty Bell

06:49.676 --> 06:50.842
into the city

06:50.844 --> 06:54.045
to keep it from falling
into British hands.

06:54.047 --> 06:56.447
For more than a year,
this American icon

06:56.449 --> 06:57.916
remained safely hidden

06:57.918 --> 07:02.053
at a local church
that still stands today.

07:02.055 --> 07:04.722
And just down the road is
an institution that celebrates

07:04.724 --> 07:08.793
the region's Revolutionary
history and more --

07:08.795 --> 07:10.829
the Lehigh Valley
Heritage Museum.

07:13.133 --> 07:16.067
The collection includes
a coal miner's hat

07:16.069 --> 07:19.237
with an oil lamp
from the early 1900s,

07:19.239 --> 07:21.873
a butter mold from the 1800s

07:21.875 --> 07:24.542
and a display
of hand-carved marionettes

07:24.544 --> 07:27.379
depicting the signing
of the U.S. Constitution.

07:30.617 --> 07:32.550
But among these antique objects

07:32.552 --> 07:35.820
is an item
of more recent vintage.

07:35.822 --> 07:40.558
The artifact is made from about
500 pages of durable paper.

07:40.560 --> 07:43.628
One page has the image
of a clock in the center.

07:43.630 --> 07:48.166
Above and below the clock
are two handwritten messages.

07:48.168 --> 07:53.304
This book recalls a chilling
Cold War game of spy versus spy.

07:53.306 --> 07:56.908
This is a tale of espionage with
a very unexpected conclusion.

07:56.910 --> 08:01.112
♪♪

08:01.114 --> 08:04.249
WILDMAN:
The early 1970s. East Germany.

08:04.251 --> 08:06.317
21-year-old Albrecht Dittrich

08:06.319 --> 08:08.319
is a hard-working
college student

08:08.321 --> 08:10.621
with a passion for science.

08:10.623 --> 08:13.124
ELEVADO: Albrecht Dittrich is
incredibly intelligent,

08:13.126 --> 08:15.326
methodical, and analytical.

08:15.328 --> 08:18.496
He trained to be a chemist
and was going for his PhD.

08:18.498 --> 08:21.599
♪♪

08:21.601 --> 08:25.036
WILDMAN: One day, Albrecht
gets an extraordinary offer.

08:25.038 --> 08:26.537
He is approached by

08:26.539 --> 08:29.507
the Soviet Committee for
State Security,

08:29.509 --> 08:32.544
also known as the KGB.

08:32.546 --> 08:34.712
They want to train him
to become a spy

08:34.714 --> 08:38.549
and eventually work as part of
a vast network of Soviet agents

08:38.551 --> 08:41.686
operating in
the United States of America.

08:41.688 --> 08:44.289
These agents will perfect
their English

08:44.291 --> 08:47.859
and get jobs specifically
in technology or in politics.

08:49.396 --> 08:51.829
WILDMAN: Lured by the prospect
of international travel,

08:51.831 --> 08:54.633
something few East Germans
have access to,

08:54.635 --> 08:56.601
Albrecht agrees.

08:56.603 --> 08:58.436
He offered himself to the KGB

08:58.438 --> 09:01.105
because of the adventure
and the intrigue.

09:01.107 --> 09:05.443
♪♪

09:05.445 --> 09:07.512
WILDMAN:
Under the tutelage of the KGB,

09:07.514 --> 09:09.214
he perfects his English,

09:09.216 --> 09:11.916
studies the intricacies of
the American culture,

09:11.918 --> 09:15.319
and learns the secrets
of Soviet spy craft.

09:15.321 --> 09:18.356
Finally, after 8 long years
of training,

09:18.358 --> 09:20.558
he is ready.

09:20.560 --> 09:22.527
♪♪

09:22.529 --> 09:24.362
In the autumn of 1978,

09:24.364 --> 09:26.865
Albrecht arrives in
New York City,

09:26.867 --> 09:31.602
obtains a driver's license
under a new name, Jack Barsky,

09:31.604 --> 09:33.871
and gets a job
as a computer programmer

09:33.873 --> 09:36.374
for a big insurance company.

09:36.376 --> 09:39.377
Initially, everything
goes smoothly.

09:39.379 --> 09:41.546
Albrecht regularly
sends back details

09:41.548 --> 09:44.715
of the company's computer system
to his handlers in Moscow.

09:44.717 --> 09:47.452
He was very dedicated to what
he was doing.

09:47.454 --> 09:49.687
♪♪

09:49.689 --> 09:51.723
WILDMAN: But then in 1986,

09:51.725 --> 09:54.626
there's a surprising
development --

09:54.628 --> 09:57.295
Albrecht falls in love.

09:57.297 --> 10:01.533
The pair marries and decides
to raise a family together.

10:01.535 --> 10:05.269
and as he adjusts more and more
to life in the United States,

10:05.271 --> 10:09.774
the Soviet spy comes
to a stunning realization --

10:09.776 --> 10:13.277
he's fighting on the wrong side.

10:13.279 --> 10:16.114
ELEVADO: He is realizing that
all that he was told

10:16.116 --> 10:19.184
about Americans
and the American lifestyle

10:19.186 --> 10:21.786
were not necessarily all true.

10:21.788 --> 10:25.790
WILDMAN: In 1988, after 10 years
of being a secret agent,

10:25.792 --> 10:28.860
Albrecht makes
a fateful decision --

10:28.862 --> 10:31.730
he'll quit spying for
the Russians.

10:31.732 --> 10:37.035
Albrecht leaves his job,
breaks all contact with the KGB,

10:37.037 --> 10:40.605
and starts a new life,
this time in the suburbs.

10:40.607 --> 10:43.675
ELEVADO: You have to disentangle
yourself from the entire system

10:43.677 --> 10:46.878
and kind of just disappear.

10:46.880 --> 10:51.115
WILDMAN: But his past is never
far behind.

10:51.117 --> 10:54.018
Albrecht's American dream
is about to become

10:54.020 --> 10:55.620
a living nightmare.

10:55.622 --> 10:59.657
♪♪

11:01.077 --> 11:03.144
♪♪

11:03.146 --> 11:07.515
In 1978, a secret agent
named Albrecht Dittrich

11:07.517 --> 11:11.185
was sent by the Soviets
to spy on the United States.

11:11.187 --> 11:14.856
But years after he arrives,
he finds the U.S. is much nicer

11:14.858 --> 11:16.357
than he thought it would be.

11:16.359 --> 11:18.626
So Dittrich cuts off ties
with Moscow

11:18.628 --> 11:22.296
and flees with his family
to the suburbs.

11:22.298 --> 11:25.467
But his clandestine past
is about to catch up with him.

11:25.469 --> 11:27.769
♪♪

11:27.771 --> 11:31.272
1992, Washington, D.C.

11:31.274 --> 11:33.641
An FBI agent named Joe Reilly

11:33.643 --> 11:36.977
gets a tip from another
Soviet defector.

11:36.979 --> 11:38.779
The turncoat says,
"There's a spy

11:38.781 --> 11:43.317
"living in the United States
under an assumed last name --

11:43.319 --> 11:46.454
Barsky."

11:46.456 --> 11:49.491
So Reilly follows up
on the intel,

11:49.493 --> 11:51.860
and he identifies
an I.T. specialist

11:51.862 --> 11:55.930
living in rural Pennsylvania
named Jack Barsky.

11:55.932 --> 11:58.600
ELEVADO: Joe Reilly is
a methodical and precise agent.

11:58.602 --> 12:01.135
He even goes as far
as acquiring the house

12:01.137 --> 12:04.539
that is right next to Barsky's.

12:04.541 --> 12:08.142
WILDMAN: And after tailing him
and wiretapping his phones,

12:08.144 --> 12:12.213
FBI agents discover that
Jack Barsky's real identity

12:12.215 --> 12:15.350
is one-time Soviet spy
Albrecht Dittrich.

12:15.352 --> 12:17.585
♪♪

12:17.587 --> 12:19.387
Agent Reilly arrests Albrecht

12:19.389 --> 12:21.623
and takes him in
for interrogation.

12:24.494 --> 12:29.164
To his surprise, the spy
is more than willing to talk.

12:29.166 --> 12:32.299
In exchange for immunity
for prosecution,

12:32.301 --> 12:34.869
Albrecht agrees to help
the FBI identify

12:34.871 --> 12:38.773
other Russian agents
also living in the U.S.

12:38.775 --> 12:42.110
ELEVADO: Albrecht had
information that the FBI wanted,

12:42.112 --> 12:43.644
and he could hand it over

12:43.646 --> 12:45.747
and continue living the life
that he was living.

12:45.749 --> 12:49.717
♪♪

12:49.719 --> 12:51.452
WILDMAN:
Eventually, the FBI roots out

12:51.454 --> 12:56.925
10 other undercover agents
posing as American citizens.

12:56.927 --> 13:01.262
It's one of the most shocking
spy busts in U.S. history.

13:01.264 --> 13:03.797
The case even goes on to serve
as the inspiration

13:03.799 --> 13:06.901
for the hit TV series
"The Americans."

13:06.903 --> 13:09.537
♪♪

13:09.539 --> 13:11.873
Today, this book
about the Cold War,

13:11.875 --> 13:15.543
signed by both Albrecht Dittrich
and Special Agent Joe Reilly,

13:15.545 --> 13:16.878
is on display

13:16.880 --> 13:18.913
at the Lehigh Valley
Heritage Museum

13:18.915 --> 13:20.882
in Allentown, Pennsylvania.

13:20.884 --> 13:24.552
It recalls the unlikely story
of a suburban spy

13:24.554 --> 13:27.222
who revealed a plot
against America.

13:27.224 --> 13:32.494
♪♪

13:32.496 --> 13:36.030
Nantucket, Massachusetts,
is located near

13:36.032 --> 13:39.901
one of the most treacherous
regions in the Atlantic Ocean,

13:39.903 --> 13:42.236
the Nantucket Shoals.

13:42.238 --> 13:46.040
Since the 1700s,
these perilously shallow waters

13:46.042 --> 13:49.877
have been the site of
more than 700 shipwrecks.

13:49.879 --> 13:53.380
So it's only fitting that
this tiny island is also home

13:53.382 --> 13:56.584
to the Nantucket
Shipwreck & Lifesaving Museum.

13:56.586 --> 14:01.255
♪♪

14:01.257 --> 14:04.692
Visitors will find a device
used to aid drowning swimmers,

14:04.694 --> 14:07.829
known as a breeches buoy,

14:07.831 --> 14:13.668
a 19th century cannon that fired
ropes to assist sinking vessels,

14:13.670 --> 14:15.803
and a set
of Congressional medals

14:15.805 --> 14:18.138
awarded to
the brave Coast Guardsmen

14:18.140 --> 14:21.843
who rescued the crew
of a stricken schooner in 1892.

14:21.845 --> 14:26.147
♪♪

14:26.149 --> 14:29.217
But hidden among
these nautical relics

14:29.219 --> 14:32.453
is a delicate object
that could be easily overlooked.

14:32.455 --> 14:35.023
HEAD: The artifact is
made of crystal.

14:35.025 --> 14:40.294
It's about 3 1/2 inches tall
by 2 inches wide.

14:40.296 --> 14:41.863
The gold etching across
the front

14:41.865 --> 14:43.565
actually says "Italia."

14:43.567 --> 14:47.435
♪♪

14:47.437 --> 14:51.338
WILDMAN: This glass recalls
an elegant ocean liner,

14:51.340 --> 14:53.207
a courageous captain,

14:53.209 --> 14:56.176
and a catastrophic collision.

14:56.178 --> 14:57.679
HEAD:
This is a story about

14:57.681 --> 15:00.381
one of the greatest
maritime disasters in history.

15:00.383 --> 15:05.753
♪♪

15:05.755 --> 15:08.323
WILDMAN: It's the 1950s.

15:08.325 --> 15:11.492
The postwar economic boom
has launched a new age

15:11.494 --> 15:13.628
of transatlantic travel.

15:13.630 --> 15:16.631
Immense liners traverse
the vast ocean,

15:16.633 --> 15:20.334
ferrying the passengers
in comfort and style.

15:20.336 --> 15:22.537
and the most luxurious
of them all

15:22.539 --> 15:25.940
is the 697-foot
Italian cruise ship

15:25.942 --> 15:28.342
the SS<i> Andrea Doria.</i>

15:28.344 --> 15:32.346
HEAD: The<i> Andrea Doria</i> was
essentially a palace on the sea.

15:32.348 --> 15:35.616
There were paintings
from world-class artists.

15:35.618 --> 15:40.121
The crystal and china
was extremely expensive.

15:40.123 --> 15:43.391
The interior of the ship
was incredibly lavish.

15:43.393 --> 15:47.228
♪♪

15:47.230 --> 15:49.964
WILDMAN: On July 17th, 1956,

15:49.966 --> 15:52.867
the<i> Andrea Doria</i>
sets out from Genoa, Italy,

15:52.869 --> 15:55.569
to New York City.
[ Ship horn blows ]

15:55.571 --> 15:59.940
Onboard are more than
1,600 passengers and crew,

15:59.942 --> 16:03.311
and at the helm is the ship's
58-year-old captain,

16:03.313 --> 16:05.046
Piero Calamai.

16:05.048 --> 16:08.182
HEAD: Captain Calamai was
a veteran of the seas.

16:08.184 --> 16:10.018
The passengers were
in extremely good hands.

16:10.020 --> 16:13.054
♪♪

16:13.056 --> 16:14.788
WILDMAN:
Eight days into the voyage,

16:14.790 --> 16:17.525
the<i> Andrea Doria</i>
is just 45 miles off

16:17.527 --> 16:19.260
the coast of Massachusetts

16:19.262 --> 16:22.863
when a blanket of thick fog
descends upon the ocean.

16:22.865 --> 16:24.732
♪♪

16:24.734 --> 16:27.001
Captain Calamai follows
standard protocol

16:27.003 --> 16:29.370
for such a circumstance.

16:29.372 --> 16:32.407
He turns on the fog signal.
He reduces speed.

16:32.409 --> 16:34.075
He's got a close eye
on the radar.

16:34.077 --> 16:36.177
♪♪

16:36.179 --> 16:39.613
WILDMAN: But as the<i> Andrea Doria</i>
edges her way through the mist,

16:39.615 --> 16:42.015
the second officer reports
that another ship

16:42.017 --> 16:44.986
is fast approaching
on the radar.

16:44.988 --> 16:49.156
In response, Captain Calamai
orders a course correction.

16:49.158 --> 16:50.924
And this
isn't necessarily something

16:50.926 --> 16:52.426
a captain
would be worried about.

16:52.428 --> 16:54.562
It's something he probably
would have run into

16:54.564 --> 16:57.164
numerous times before.

16:57.166 --> 17:00.567
WILDMAN: But then,
less than half an hour later,

17:00.569 --> 17:04.605
the lights of a huge vessel
loom through the fog.

17:04.607 --> 17:09.042
It's another ocean liner,
the MS<i> Stockholm,</i>

17:09.044 --> 17:12.313
and it's headed straight for
the<i> Andrea Doria.</i>

17:12.315 --> 17:15.549
-The situation is dire...
[ Ship horn blows ]

17:15.551 --> 17:19.087
...but the Captain is likely
experiencing fear.

17:19.089 --> 17:22.223
WILDMAN: Calamai orders
a hard turn to the port side,

17:22.225 --> 17:24.192
but its too late.

17:24.194 --> 17:27.562
[ Loud crash ]
The two ships
slam into each other.

17:27.564 --> 17:36.204
♪♪

17:36.206 --> 17:39.974
46 passengers and crew
on the<i> Andrea Doria</i>

17:39.976 --> 17:45.413
and five on the<i> Stockholm</i>
are killed in the impact.

17:45.415 --> 17:48.850
Not only that, but the collision
has punched a massive hole

17:48.852 --> 17:50.885
in the<i> Andrea Doria's</i> hull.

17:50.887 --> 17:54.088
Water starts to come in.
People are screaming.

17:54.090 --> 17:57.825
It's a terrifying situation.

17:57.827 --> 18:02.830
WILDMAN: The luxury ocean liner
begins to sink.

18:02.832 --> 18:06.634
Miraculously, the<i> Stockholm</i>
is still seaworthy,

18:06.636 --> 18:08.069
but it's too badly damaged

18:08.071 --> 18:10.738
to take on
the<i> Andrea Doria's</i> passengers.

18:10.740 --> 18:13.507
[ Telegraph beeping ]
-So Calamai sends out an S.O.S.

18:13.509 --> 18:16.277
and orders everyone
to the lifeboats.

18:16.279 --> 18:18.679
Before long, the Captain
and everyone on board

18:18.681 --> 18:21.783
start feeling the ship list.

18:23.453 --> 18:25.853
WILDMAN: The passengers find
reaching the lifeboats

18:25.855 --> 18:27.288
nearly impossible.

18:27.290 --> 18:29.924
Most of the lifeboats
were inaccessible

18:29.926 --> 18:33.160
because of the way
the ship was sinking.

18:33.162 --> 18:36.363
It looked liked the<i> Andrea Doria</i>
was going to sink

18:36.365 --> 18:38.533
with thousands of passengers
onboard.

18:38.535 --> 18:40.735
♪♪

18:40.737 --> 18:44.005
WILDMAN: How will the passengers
escape a watery fate?

18:44.007 --> 18:46.440
[ Screaming ]

18:47.994 --> 18:49.960
♪♪

18:49.962 --> 18:52.530
It's 1956.

18:52.532 --> 18:54.865
The world's most luxurious
ocean liner,

18:54.867 --> 18:59.337
the SS<i> Andrea Doria,</i> is en route
from Italy to New York.

18:59.339 --> 19:03.875
Onboard are more than
1,600 passengers and crew.

19:03.877 --> 19:05.543
But 8 days into the journey,

19:05.545 --> 19:09.981
the<i> Andrea Doria</i>
collides with another ship,

19:09.983 --> 19:13.517
and now the massive craft
is starting to sink.

19:13.519 --> 19:15.286
♪♪

19:15.288 --> 19:17.288
The<i> Andrea Doria's</i>
distress call

19:17.290 --> 19:20.591
is picked up by a vessel
some 40 miles away,

19:20.593 --> 19:24.228
a passenger ship named
the<i> Ile de France</i>

19:24.230 --> 19:28.098
under the command of
Captain Raoul de Beaudéan.

19:28.100 --> 19:30.668
The captain orders his crew
to set a course

19:30.670 --> 19:33.571
for the<i> Andrea Doria.</i>

19:33.573 --> 19:36.974
Not only was the ship coming
to rescue the passengers,

19:36.976 --> 19:41.612
but it was about twice the size
of the<i> Andrea Doria.</i>

19:41.614 --> 19:44.548
WILDMAN:
And when the<i> Ile de France</i>
arrives 2 hours later,

19:44.550 --> 19:47.985
de Beaudéan springs into action.

19:47.987 --> 19:50.187
He uses his ship's
massive floodlights

19:50.189 --> 19:51.589
to illuminate the sea

19:51.591 --> 19:55.859
and drops 10 lifeboats
into the water.

19:55.861 --> 19:58.729
His resourceful crew
swiftly ferries passengers

19:58.731 --> 20:02.667
from the sinking<i> Andrea Doria</i>
back to the<i> Ile de France.</i>

20:02.669 --> 20:07.638
The<i> Ile de France</i> was able
to take on over 750 passengers.

20:07.640 --> 20:09.140
WILDMAN: In the hours
that follow,

20:09.142 --> 20:12.410
a flotilla of other ships
arrives on the scene

20:12.412 --> 20:16.447
to help save the remaining
passengers and crew.

20:16.449 --> 20:19.016
Captain Piero Calamai
is the last person

20:19.018 --> 20:21.018
to step off the<i> Andrea Doria.</i>

20:21.020 --> 20:24.888
♪♪

20:24.890 --> 20:26.290
The event goes down

20:26.292 --> 20:28.225
as one of the most successful
rescue missions

20:28.227 --> 20:30.828
in maritime history.

20:30.830 --> 20:33.964
Over 1,600 passengers
were saved.

20:33.966 --> 20:35.433
WILDMAN: On July 27th,

20:35.435 --> 20:38.302
the<i> Ile de France</i>
and the damaged<i> Stockholm</i>

20:38.304 --> 20:40.705
dock in New York harbor,

20:40.707 --> 20:42.773
but the story doesn't end there.

20:42.775 --> 20:45.309
♪♪

20:45.311 --> 20:48.446
A few days after the sinking
of the<i> Andrea Doria,</i>

20:48.448 --> 20:50.981
two curious divers
descend to the depths

20:50.983 --> 20:54.852
to gather artifacts
from the submerged vessel.

20:54.854 --> 20:59.957
Among the objects they retrieve
is this crystal aperitif glass.

20:59.959 --> 21:01.459
Today, it is on display

21:01.461 --> 21:04.194
at the Nantucket Shipwreck
& Lifesaving Museum

21:04.196 --> 21:06.464
in Massachusetts.

21:06.466 --> 21:09.667
It recalls the ignominious fate
of a cruise liner

21:09.669 --> 21:12.570
that's now anchored
at the bottom of the sea.

21:15.875 --> 21:17.041
♪♪

21:17.043 --> 21:19.610
Rochester, New York,
is the former home

21:19.612 --> 21:23.147
of the noted entrepreneur
George Eastman.

21:23.149 --> 21:28.151
In 1892, he founded what would
become the Kodak Company.

21:28.153 --> 21:30.621
Today, the tycoon's
one-time residence

21:30.623 --> 21:34.992
is now an institution
dedicated to his legacy,

21:34.994 --> 21:38.362
the George Eastman Museum.

21:38.364 --> 21:42.366
Keen-eyed visitors can spot one
of the first handheld cameras,

21:42.368 --> 21:45.870
known as
the Folding Pocket Kodak,

21:45.872 --> 21:48.572
one of the first machines built
to view motion pictures,

21:48.574 --> 21:51.342
called a mutoscope,

21:51.344 --> 21:54.778
and a camera designed by NASA
for the lunar orbiter.

21:54.780 --> 21:57.681
♪♪

21:57.683 --> 22:01.651
And among these innovative items
is a device that once belonged

22:01.653 --> 22:04.655
to one of photography's
greatest talents.

22:04.657 --> 22:08.759
It's a rectangular-shaped object
made of two wooden boxes

22:08.761 --> 22:12.028
and two metal and glass lenses.

22:12.030 --> 22:15.432
At the back, there is
an opaque glass screen

22:15.434 --> 22:18.936
on which images
can be projected.

22:18.938 --> 22:21.738
WILDMAN: The man behind
this antique camera is linked

22:21.740 --> 22:25.176
to the spectacular eyes
of America's greatest president.

22:25.178 --> 22:27.845
MAROD: This is the story
of personal vanity,

22:27.847 --> 22:31.282
political necessity,
and photographic trickery.

22:31.284 --> 22:35.319
♪♪

22:35.321 --> 22:37.554
WILDMAN: It's 1859.

22:37.556 --> 22:39.823
Mathew Brady
is one of the most popular

22:39.825 --> 22:42.759
portrait photographers
in New York.

22:42.761 --> 22:46.030
Among the famous names
who have sat before him

22:46.032 --> 22:48.299
are Andrew Jackson,

22:48.301 --> 22:52.302
Edgar Allen Poe,
and James Fenimore Cooper.

22:52.304 --> 22:54.772
MAROD: Mathew Brady was really

22:54.774 --> 22:57.641
the superstar photographer
of the day.

22:57.643 --> 23:00.578
♪♪

23:00.580 --> 23:02.846
WILDMAN:
The secret of his success?

23:02.848 --> 23:05.048
Attention to detail.

23:05.050 --> 23:07.785
MAROD: He was interested
in how the lighting,

23:07.787 --> 23:11.222
the backdrop, the props,
how the person was posed

23:11.224 --> 23:13.557
could change
how a photograph looked

23:13.559 --> 23:15.659
and what the photograph said
to the viewer.

23:15.661 --> 23:19.496
♪♪

23:19.498 --> 23:22.399
WILDMAN: And in 1860,
this photographic whiz kid

23:22.401 --> 23:25.603
faces his biggest challenge yet.

23:25.605 --> 23:28.606
Brady is approached
by a 51-year-old legislator

23:28.608 --> 23:30.441
from Illinois
who has set his sights

23:30.443 --> 23:34.879
on the highest office
in the land --

23:34.881 --> 23:37.247
Abraham Lincoln.

23:37.249 --> 23:40.050
MAROD: Abraham Lincoln
had a very rustic background.

23:40.052 --> 23:43.753
He had spent 8 years on
the Illinois state legislature,

23:43.755 --> 23:46.290
and now he wants
to run for president.

23:48.294 --> 23:49.960
WILDMAN:
But the race to secure

23:49.962 --> 23:51.695
the Republican
presidential nomination

23:51.697 --> 23:54.031
is far from certain,

23:54.033 --> 23:56.767
and Lincoln believes
one thing above all others

23:56.769 --> 23:59.236
is holding him back --

23:59.238 --> 24:02.373
his looks.

24:02.375 --> 24:05.576
MAROD: Abraham Lincoln
was described by his own wife

24:05.578 --> 24:09.079
as being "not pretty."

24:09.081 --> 24:12.716
He had the super long neck,
these big hands,

24:12.718 --> 24:15.986
a lot of very deep wrinkles.

24:15.988 --> 24:17.388
WILDMAN:
And she's not the only one

24:17.390 --> 24:21.758
to cast aspersions
on Honest Abe's visage.

24:21.760 --> 24:23.527
Newspaper cartoonists of the day

24:23.529 --> 24:25.129
frequently depicted
the politician

24:25.131 --> 24:28.799
as having a neck
as long as a giraffe's,

24:28.801 --> 24:30.935
ridiculous large hands,

24:30.937 --> 24:33.270
and a grossly misshapen head.

24:33.272 --> 24:36.073
♪♪

24:36.075 --> 24:40.811
Such images play a crucial role
in shaping public perception.

24:40.813 --> 24:42.680
Lincoln knew that these drawings

24:42.682 --> 24:45.349
could be very,
very unflattering,

24:45.351 --> 24:47.618
and his opponent
used that against him.

24:47.620 --> 24:51.154
♪♪

24:51.156 --> 24:54.758
WILDMAN: So to counter these
cartoonish characterizations,

24:54.760 --> 24:57.027
Lincoln has sought out
Mathew Brady,

24:57.029 --> 24:58.629
the one photographer he believes

24:58.631 --> 25:02.632
can make him look properly fit
for the White House.

25:02.634 --> 25:05.502
Lincoln was hoping
that Mathew Brady

25:05.504 --> 25:07.838
could provide
a picture that said,

25:07.840 --> 25:09.840
"I am President
of the United States."

25:09.842 --> 25:12.976
♪♪

25:12.978 --> 25:14.311
WILDMAN:
The assignment will take

25:14.313 --> 25:16.714
every ounce of Brady's skill.

25:16.716 --> 25:19.583
Nevertheless,
he jumps at the chance.

25:19.585 --> 25:22.253
Taking a flattering photo
in the 1850s

25:22.255 --> 25:23.921
was hugely challenging.

25:23.923 --> 25:25.789
We didn't have airbrushing.

25:25.791 --> 25:27.491
We didn't have Photoshop.

25:27.493 --> 25:29.927
We didn't have filters.

25:29.929 --> 25:31.662
WILDMAN:
So how will Mathew Brady create

25:31.664 --> 25:34.665
a portrait
worthy of a president?

25:35.968 --> 25:38.101
♪♪

25:38.103 --> 25:40.170
It's 1860.

25:40.172 --> 25:42.773
Photographer Mathew Brady
has just received

25:42.775 --> 25:44.641
an intriguing commission

25:44.643 --> 25:48.646
to photograph the presidential
candidate Abraham Lincoln.

25:48.648 --> 25:51.581
Lincoln fears that voters
will find him ugly,

25:51.583 --> 25:54.517
so he wants Brady
to disguise his lanky frame,

25:54.519 --> 25:56.887
gaunt face, and large hands.

25:56.889 --> 26:00.891
So how will Brady touch up this
future president's portrait?

26:02.461 --> 26:05.029
On February 27, 1860,

26:05.031 --> 26:07.831
Abraham Lincoln arrives
at Mathew Brady's studio

26:07.833 --> 26:09.800
for his portrait session.

26:09.802 --> 26:12.002
Brady employs
creative techniques

26:12.004 --> 26:15.638
to conceal Lincoln's
perceived imperfections.

26:15.640 --> 26:19.877
He pulls up Lincoln's collar
to cover his long neck.

26:19.879 --> 26:23.113
Then, to disguise Lincoln's
most unflattering features,

26:23.115 --> 26:25.682
he creates an optical illusion.

26:25.684 --> 26:29.019
MAROD: He places Lincoln's
left hand on a stack of books

26:29.021 --> 26:32.622
and he has Lincoln push his
left arm back just a little bit,

26:32.624 --> 26:35.859
and this creates an illusion
that the hand is smaller.

26:39.732 --> 26:41.498
WILDMAN:
With Lincoln in position,

26:41.500 --> 26:45.569
Brady adds a brilliant
and ingenious final flourish.

26:45.571 --> 26:48.138
MAROD: He actually
flooded Lincoln's face

26:48.140 --> 26:49.840
with this bright light,

26:49.842 --> 26:54.011
and this hid
all of Lincoln's wrinkles.

26:54.013 --> 26:56.313
WILDMAN:
With everything in place,

26:56.315 --> 26:58.582
Brady snaps the photograph.

26:58.584 --> 27:01.618
♪♪

27:01.620 --> 27:03.053
Later that day,

27:03.055 --> 27:06.056
he shows the developed picture
to Lincoln.

27:06.058 --> 27:08.459
MAROD:
Lincoln looks at that photo.

27:08.461 --> 27:11.928
He says, "Brady has done
the impossible.

27:11.930 --> 27:16.600
I see someone who is worth being
President of the United States."

27:16.602 --> 27:18.602
WILDMAN:
Lincoln has the portrait

27:18.604 --> 27:21.805
printed on postcards,
buttons, and stationery,

27:21.807 --> 27:25.075
and has them distributed
across the country.

27:25.077 --> 27:26.910
The response is overwhelming.

27:26.912 --> 27:28.478
MAROD: For the first time,

27:28.480 --> 27:31.681
Americans see
a photograph of Lincoln,

27:31.683 --> 27:33.817
and they like what they see.

27:33.819 --> 27:35.085
He's presidential.

27:35.087 --> 27:36.487
♪♪

27:36.489 --> 27:40.123
WILDMAN: On November 6, 1860,
Abraham Lincoln is elected

27:40.125 --> 27:43.894
the 16th president
of the United States.

27:43.896 --> 27:46.396
Lincoln even said,
"Mathew Brady made me

27:46.398 --> 27:49.199
President of the United States."

27:49.201 --> 27:52.836
And after this, he is just
a huge fan of Mathew Brady.

27:52.838 --> 27:56.239
He took 30 photographs
of Abraham Lincoln

27:56.241 --> 27:58.641
throughout his life.

27:58.643 --> 28:00.911
WILDMAN: Two of Brady's photos
of the President

28:00.913 --> 28:02.980
even become the basis
for Lincoln's image

28:02.982 --> 28:05.482
on the penny and $5 bill.

28:05.484 --> 28:07.984
♪♪

28:07.986 --> 28:11.355
Today, this camera,
once owned by Mathew Brady,

28:11.357 --> 28:13.824
is on display at
the George Eastman Museum

28:13.826 --> 28:15.826
in Rochester, New York.

28:15.828 --> 28:18.328
It recalls
the pioneering photographer

28:18.330 --> 28:20.764
who helped develop
the image of a president.

28:20.766 --> 28:25.468
♪♪

28:25.470 --> 28:27.604
Located in the heart of Scotland

28:27.606 --> 28:30.941
is the windswept city
of Stirling.

28:30.943 --> 28:32.342
Best known as the site

28:32.344 --> 28:34.211
of freedom fighter
William Wallace's

28:34.213 --> 28:37.581
14th century victory
over the English,

28:37.583 --> 28:39.616
today, it's home to
an institution

28:39.618 --> 28:43.453
that celebrates
the warrior's life and legacy --

28:43.455 --> 28:45.021
the National Wallace Monument.

28:45.023 --> 28:49.759
♪♪

28:49.761 --> 28:53.464
Here, visitors can find exhibits
and replicas of medieval armor

28:53.466 --> 28:57.568
and weaponry
used in the historic battle,

28:57.570 --> 29:01.572
including a 25-pound
chain mail shirt,

29:01.574 --> 29:04.674
a steel helmet worn by knights,

29:04.676 --> 29:07.110
and a lethal iron mace.

29:07.112 --> 29:09.379
♪♪

29:09.381 --> 29:11.115
And looking over these treasures

29:11.117 --> 29:14.117
is an image
of the museum's namesake.

29:14.119 --> 29:15.719
LEVINE: This artifact
is very visually striking.

29:15.721 --> 29:18.054
It glows.

29:18.056 --> 29:22.192
It's about 5 feet high,
about a foot and a half wide.

29:22.194 --> 29:26.296
The man depicted
is clearly ready for war.

29:26.298 --> 29:29.265
WILDMAN: This artifact
speaks to the tragic origins

29:29.267 --> 29:31.568
of Scotland's greatest hero,

29:31.570 --> 29:34.571
and it recalls an epic tale
of romance,

29:34.573 --> 29:37.374
rebellion, and revenge.

29:37.376 --> 29:39.943
This is the story of a man
who gave hope to a nation.

29:39.945 --> 29:46.049
♪♪

29:46.051 --> 29:48.585
WILDMAN: It's 1297.

29:48.587 --> 29:50.954
William Wallace is
a landowning nobleman

29:50.956 --> 29:54.625
living in the southern
Scottish town of Lanark.

29:54.627 --> 29:57.660
LEVINE: William Wallace
is a low-ranking Scottish lord.

29:57.662 --> 30:01.631
He believes very strongly
in the pride of his nation,

30:01.633 --> 30:03.166
but at the same time,
he was pursuing

30:03.168 --> 30:05.802
his interests in a young woman
in the town.

30:08.974 --> 30:11.175
WILDMAN: The object
of the young lord's affections

30:11.177 --> 30:14.744
is a beautiful maiden
named Marion Braidfute.

30:14.746 --> 30:17.714
LEVINE:
Accounts tell us that Marion was
a very attractive young woman.

30:17.716 --> 30:19.550
He sees her as his future.

30:22.187 --> 30:25.122
WILDMAN: But someone stands
in Wallace's way --

30:25.124 --> 30:28.859
a cruel English officer
named William Heselrig

30:28.861 --> 30:31.327
also has his eye on Marion.

30:31.329 --> 30:33.463
And with Scotland under
English rule,

30:33.465 --> 30:37.167
Wallace is powerless to stop
the lawman's advances.

30:37.169 --> 30:40.536
Heselrig forces Marion
to become engaged to him.

30:40.538 --> 30:42.439
♪♪

30:42.441 --> 30:45.342
LEVINE: Marion did not want
to marry Heselrig,

30:45.344 --> 30:47.010
but these were not times

30:47.012 --> 30:49.946
where people could just do
what they wanted to do.

30:49.948 --> 30:52.682
WILDMAN: Wallace refuses to
abandon his true love

30:52.684 --> 30:55.152
to this lustful
English overlord.

30:57.422 --> 31:01.758
In secret, Wallace and Marion
continue their relationship,

31:01.760 --> 31:05.362
but their romantic liaisons
come with a great risk.

31:05.364 --> 31:08.765
LEVINE: If William Wallace
was actually caught with Marion,

31:08.767 --> 31:10.500
this was incredibly dangerous.

31:10.502 --> 31:13.704
So they had to be
very, very careful.

31:13.706 --> 31:16.172
WILDMAN: Despite
their attempts at secrecy,

31:16.174 --> 31:17.974
the couple are found out.

31:17.976 --> 31:19.843
LEVINE:
Every Sunday after church,

31:19.845 --> 31:21.377
William Wallace would visit her,

31:21.379 --> 31:24.081
and on one occasion, he was
spotted leaving her house

31:24.083 --> 31:26.116
by an English soldier.

31:26.118 --> 31:30.654
WILDMAN: The soldier threatens
to expose the affair,

31:30.656 --> 31:33.523
so Wallace kills him.

31:33.525 --> 31:36.927
The commotion attracts other
English soldiers to the scene

31:36.929 --> 31:39.996
and Wallace is forced
to run for his life.

31:39.998 --> 31:41.732
LEVINE:
Now this raised the stakes.

31:41.734 --> 31:43.600
William Wallace was now
an outlaw.

31:43.602 --> 31:46.436
♪♪

31:46.438 --> 31:49.673
WILDMAN: Wallace escapes to
the outskirts of Lanark,

31:49.675 --> 31:54.678
where he waits for the uproar
over the killing to die down.

31:54.680 --> 31:58.882
But then he receives
heartbreaking news.

31:58.884 --> 32:02.552
Word of his rendezvous
with Marion reached Heselrig,

32:02.554 --> 32:04.821
and in a fit of jealous rage,

32:04.823 --> 32:08.091
the cruel sheriff
had her executed.

32:08.093 --> 32:11.161
Wallace was
absolutely devastated.

32:11.163 --> 32:14.898
He was already furious
at the English.

32:14.900 --> 32:18.768
Now to hear this,
he must have his revenge.

32:18.770 --> 32:22.406
WILDMAN: The scorn Scotsman
is about to embark on a crusade

32:22.408 --> 32:24.241
that will echo through the ages.

32:24.243 --> 32:25.609
♪♪

32:26.946 --> 32:28.879
♪♪

32:28.881 --> 32:31.114
It's 1297.

32:31.116 --> 32:32.982
A Scottish lord
named William Wallace

32:32.984 --> 32:36.119
is in love with a young woman
named Marion.

32:36.121 --> 32:37.520
But he has a rival,

32:37.522 --> 32:41.224
a cruel English officer
named William Heselrig.

32:41.226 --> 32:43.493
And when Heselrig finds out
that Wallace and Marion

32:43.495 --> 32:45.995
have been seeing each other
in secret,

32:45.997 --> 32:48.632
Heselrig has Marion executed.

32:48.634 --> 32:50.633
What Wallace does next will echo

32:50.635 --> 32:53.503
through the history books
to this very day.

32:53.505 --> 32:55.972
♪♪

32:55.974 --> 32:57.740
To exact his revenge,

32:57.742 --> 33:01.845
William Wallace rallies
a small band of Scots.

33:01.847 --> 33:06.582
Under the cloak of darkness,
they sneak into Heselrig's house

33:06.584 --> 33:08.785
and kill him in his sleep.

33:08.787 --> 33:10.120
[ Crow caws ]

33:10.122 --> 33:13.790
But Wallace's quest for
vengeance doesn't stop there.

33:13.792 --> 33:16.126
LEVINE: Wallace has
had a measure of revenge,

33:16.128 --> 33:17.527
but its not enough for him.

33:17.529 --> 33:23.667
He wants to bring freedom
to the Scottish people.

33:23.669 --> 33:26.736
WILDMAN:
The fighter rallies thousands
of his fellow countrymen

33:26.738 --> 33:29.873
to full-on rebellion against
their English oppressors.

33:29.875 --> 33:33.543
♪♪

33:33.545 --> 33:38.148
And on September 11, 1297,
Wallace leads the Scots

33:38.150 --> 33:40.516
to a resounding victory
over the English at

33:40.518 --> 33:42.886
the "Battle of Stirling Bridge."

33:42.888 --> 33:46.156
LEVINE:
He won against all the odds,

33:46.158 --> 33:48.358
and he became
the protector of Scotland.

33:48.360 --> 33:52.262
♪♪

33:52.264 --> 33:55.498
WILDMAN: Eventually,
Wallace's luck runs out.

33:55.500 --> 34:00.170
In 1305, he is captured
and killed by the English,

34:00.172 --> 34:03.240
but his armies
continue their fight.

34:03.242 --> 34:08.111
The seed of resistance
had very much been sown.

34:08.113 --> 34:12.449
WILDMAN: In 1328,
23 years after Wallace's death,

34:12.451 --> 34:15.652
the Scots and English sign
the Treaty of Edinburgh,

34:15.654 --> 34:18.921
granting Scotland independence.

34:18.923 --> 34:22.592
More than 650 years
after this historic moment,

34:22.594 --> 34:25.595
the freedom fighter's tale
is told on the silver screen

34:25.597 --> 34:31.935
in the 1996 Academy Award
winning film "Braveheart."

34:31.937 --> 34:35.071
William Wallace is still
remembered as a great hero.

34:36.275 --> 34:38.408
♪♪

34:38.410 --> 34:40.343
WILDMAN: Today,
this stained glass window

34:40.345 --> 34:42.145
depicting
the legendary freedom fighter

34:42.147 --> 34:45.147
is on display
at the National Wallace Monument

34:45.149 --> 34:47.750
in Stirling, Scotland.

34:47.752 --> 34:50.019
It's a testament to
a valiant leader

34:50.021 --> 34:53.356
and the tragic romance
that sparked a revolution.

34:53.358 --> 34:58.094
♪♪

34:58.096 --> 35:00.263
40 miles north of San Francisco

35:00.265 --> 35:03.433
is the charming town
of Petaluma.

35:03.435 --> 35:05.602
During World War II, it was home

35:05.604 --> 35:09.305
to the largest code breaking
station on the west coast.

35:09.307 --> 35:12.108
Today, this legacy and more
is celebrated

35:12.110 --> 35:14.511
at the Military Antiques
& Museum.

35:14.513 --> 35:18.381
♪♪

35:18.383 --> 35:22.385
The collection includes
a German helmet from 1915

35:22.387 --> 35:25.321
called a pickelhaube,

35:25.323 --> 35:27.924
a brass samovar
used by Russian officers

35:27.926 --> 35:30.693
to make tea during World War I,

35:30.695 --> 35:34.431
and a U.S. Army military police
Jeep from the 1940s.

35:36.935 --> 35:39.235
But amid these hard,
metallic objects

35:39.237 --> 35:41.771
is a small item made of paper.

35:41.773 --> 35:44.574
HURLEY: The artifact can fit
in the palm of your hand.

35:44.576 --> 35:47.510
Across the front of the cover
in bold letters,

35:47.512 --> 35:51.515
it says "Operations in Snow
and Extreme Cold."

35:51.517 --> 35:52.682
♪♪

35:52.684 --> 35:54.284
WILDMAN:
This field guide recalls

35:54.286 --> 35:56.486
a harrowing tale of survival

35:56.488 --> 35:59.823
in one of the harshest
environments on Earth.

35:59.825 --> 36:01.858
HURLEY:
This is an incredible story

36:01.860 --> 36:04.327
set in the middle of
the Alaskan wilderness.

36:04.329 --> 36:09.165
♪♪

36:09.167 --> 36:13.103
WILDMAN:
1943. Fairbanks, Alaska.

36:13.105 --> 36:17.307
This remote city, only 100 miles
south of the Arctic Circle,

36:17.309 --> 36:20.577
is home to
a vital military base --

36:20.579 --> 36:23.045
Ladd Army Airfield.

36:23.047 --> 36:24.714
HURLEY:
Ladd Army Airfield was used

36:24.716 --> 36:27.550
to take equipment and aircrafts

36:27.552 --> 36:29.653
and test them in extreme cold.

36:29.655 --> 36:31.187
♪♪

36:31.189 --> 36:32.922
WILDMAN: On December 21st,

36:32.924 --> 36:36.459
a B-24 Liberator
with five crewmen

36:36.461 --> 36:40.664
takes off from the airfield
on a routine test flight.

36:40.666 --> 36:42.532
The crew's mission
is to fly a loop

36:42.534 --> 36:44.334
between Fairbanks
and the Yukon River

36:44.336 --> 36:46.403
before returning to base.

36:46.405 --> 36:48.337
♪♪

36:48.339 --> 36:50.273
But 90 minutes into the flight,

36:50.275 --> 36:52.509
the radio operators
at Ladd Airfield

36:52.511 --> 36:54.544
get a troubling transmission.

36:54.546 --> 36:56.746
HURLEY: The plane was having
engine problems,

36:56.748 --> 36:59.082
goes in a fast,
uncontrollable tailspin.

37:00.819 --> 37:04.955
WILDMAN: The radio operators ask
the crew for their location,

37:04.957 --> 37:07.023
but there is no response,

37:07.025 --> 37:09.793
sparking fear that
the aircraft may have crashed.

37:09.795 --> 37:14.430
♪♪

37:14.432 --> 37:16.899
So officials launch
an aerial search of the area,

37:16.901 --> 37:18.835
surrounding
the last known coordinates

37:18.837 --> 37:21.571
of the missing plane.

37:21.573 --> 37:24.040
And over the course of 6 days,

37:24.042 --> 37:27.310
the search teams scour
nearly 40,000 square miles

37:27.312 --> 37:30.380
of Alaskan wilderness,

37:30.382 --> 37:32.181
but the missing aircraft
and its crew

37:32.183 --> 37:34.517
are nowhere to be found.

37:34.519 --> 37:37.587
The situation
was obviously dire.

37:37.589 --> 37:38.988
♪♪

37:38.990 --> 37:40.790
WILDMAN: On December 27th,

37:40.792 --> 37:42.858
it's decided
that there is no way

37:42.860 --> 37:46.929
any of the survivors of
the crash could still be alive.

37:46.931 --> 37:48.798
The search is called off.

37:48.800 --> 37:51.968
This was December in Alaska.

37:51.970 --> 37:53.403
It was cold.

37:53.405 --> 37:55.204
It was remote.

37:55.206 --> 37:57.273
This was a sure death sentence.

37:59.077 --> 38:01.143
WILDMAN: But then,
almost 3 months later

38:01.145 --> 38:05.815
on March 14th,
something incredible happens.

38:05.817 --> 38:07.617
A man staggers
up to the entrance

38:07.619 --> 38:10.720
of the Ladd Army Airfield.

38:10.722 --> 38:13.957
The guards immediately
recognize him.

38:13.959 --> 38:15.892
He is Lieutenant Leon Crane,

38:15.894 --> 38:18.461
one of the crewmen
from the missing flight.

38:18.463 --> 38:21.097
People at base
couldn't have been happier.

38:21.099 --> 38:22.699
WILDMAN:
But the mystery remains.

38:22.701 --> 38:26.369
What happened to the plane
and the rest of the crew?

38:27.856 --> 38:29.956
♪♪

38:29.958 --> 38:32.058
It's 1944.

38:32.060 --> 38:34.760
A B-24 bomber has disappeared

38:34.762 --> 38:37.931
while on a test flight
over the Alaskan wilderness.

38:37.933 --> 38:42.134
The crew of five U.S. airmen
are all presumed dead.

38:42.136 --> 38:45.605
But now, nearly 3 months after
the plane was lost,

38:45.607 --> 38:48.975
the missing pilot
returns to base.

38:48.977 --> 38:51.011
So how did he survive?

38:51.013 --> 38:53.079
♪♪

38:53.081 --> 38:54.881
At Ladd Army Airfield,

38:54.883 --> 38:58.818
pilot Leon Crane recounts
an incredible tale of survival.

38:58.820 --> 39:01.087
♪♪

39:01.089 --> 39:03.890
About 2 hours into
the ill-fated flight,

39:03.892 --> 39:06.726
one of the plane's
four engines failed.

39:06.728 --> 39:09.229
Crane bailed out before
the aircraft crashed

39:09.231 --> 39:10.897
into the frozen tundra.

39:10.899 --> 39:12.932
[ Loud crash ]

39:12.934 --> 39:16.603
Tragically, he was
the only survivor.

39:16.605 --> 39:20.139
But even though he escaped
the doomed plane,

39:20.141 --> 39:22.642
his chances of making it
back to civilization

39:22.644 --> 39:25.278
were perilously slim.

39:25.280 --> 39:27.414
All the supplies Crane
needed to survive

39:27.416 --> 39:28.948
were destroyed on the plane.

39:28.950 --> 39:31.150
♪♪

39:31.152 --> 39:34.654
WILDMAN: Desperate to stay warm
in the subzero temperatures,

39:34.656 --> 39:36.956
Crane set about making a fire.

39:36.958 --> 39:40.427
HURLEY: So Crane gathered
wood shavings, pine needles,

39:40.429 --> 39:42.495
and anything he could.

39:42.497 --> 39:44.164
WILDMAN: With the fire ablaze,

39:44.166 --> 39:46.299
he was able to make it
through the night.

39:46.301 --> 39:49.369
♪♪

39:49.371 --> 39:52.438
The next day, Crane constructed
a makeshift camp

39:52.440 --> 39:55.174
where he waited for rescue.

39:55.176 --> 39:58.144
But search teams were unable
to locate the crashed plane

39:58.146 --> 40:00.513
in the vast Alaskan wilderness,

40:00.515 --> 40:02.581
and rescue never came.

40:02.583 --> 40:06.986
♪♪

40:06.988 --> 40:10.356
After 9 days
with no hope in sight,

40:10.358 --> 40:15.261
he set out on his own
in search of civilization.

40:15.263 --> 40:17.130
As he made his way through
the forest,

40:17.132 --> 40:19.465
Crane came across a stream.

40:19.467 --> 40:22.869
In hopes of finding
a settlement, he followed it.

40:22.871 --> 40:24.804
The decision paid off.

40:24.806 --> 40:27.407
The waterway led him
to an empty hunting cabin

40:27.409 --> 40:29.676
stocked with canned goods.

40:29.678 --> 40:31.811
HURLEY: Crane couldn't have
been more relieved.

40:31.813 --> 40:34.681
He had everything he needed
for the rest of the journey.

40:34.683 --> 40:38.417
♪♪

40:38.419 --> 40:41.554
WILDMAN: After a few weeks
of rest, he continued walking,

40:41.556 --> 40:43.422
and eventually found
a small town

40:43.424 --> 40:46.226
where he hitched a ride
back to the air base.

40:46.228 --> 40:49.162
Crane was ecstatic.
He was safe.

40:49.164 --> 40:53.032
♪♪

40:53.034 --> 40:56.369
WILDMAN: Crane serves in
the Army until the end of 1945

40:56.371 --> 40:57.770
and later becomes

40:57.772 --> 41:00.473
an aeronautical engineer
for Boeing.

41:00.475 --> 41:03.376
His arctic adventure
is recalled to this day

41:03.378 --> 41:07.113
as one of the military's
greatest feats of endurance.

41:07.115 --> 41:10.984
HURLEY: Crane had survived in
the Alaskan wilderness.

41:10.986 --> 41:15.054
I can't think of a better
example of man versus nature.

41:15.056 --> 41:16.255
This is it.

41:16.257 --> 41:19.725
♪♪

41:19.727 --> 41:21.060
WILDMAN: A field manual

41:21.062 --> 41:24.197
for "Operations in Snow
and Extreme Cold,"

41:24.199 --> 41:26.533
that contains a host
of survival techniques,

41:26.535 --> 41:29.636
including the ones
employed by Leon Crane,

41:29.638 --> 41:31.204
sits on display

41:31.206 --> 41:32.872
at the Military Antiques
& Museum

41:32.874 --> 41:35.541
in Petaluma, California.

41:35.543 --> 41:38.277
It's a testament
to a stranded aviator

41:38.279 --> 41:40.713
who took on Alaska and won.

41:40.715 --> 41:44.584
♪♪

41:44.586 --> 41:47.020
From a Scottish hero

41:47.022 --> 41:49.655
to a real-life Lassie,

41:49.657 --> 41:51.491
a maritime disaster

41:51.493 --> 41:54.193
to a presidential portrait...

41:54.195 --> 41:57.363
I'm Don Wildman, and these are
the mysteries at the museum.
